{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506763"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:46:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:46:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2569"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2569"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.09,0.13,0.16,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2569"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28709"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6370"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2691"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with intermittent abdominal pain and foul-smelling diarrhoea for the past nine months. He recently developed foul-smelling anal discharge. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 12-pack-year smoking history. On examination, his pulse rate is 89/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals right lower quadrant tenderness, but no guarding. Perianal examination reveals a posterior skin tag and a fistula draining foul-smelling purulent discharge. Oral examination reveals several shallow ulcers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following type of renal stones is this patient particularly at risk of developing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium oxalate stones","Calcium phosphate stones","Cystine stones","Magnesium ammonium phosphate stones","Uric acid stones"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with chronic non-bloody diarrhoea, anal fistula, and oral ulcers most likely has Crohn\u2019s disease (CD). CD is an inflammatory disorder of the bowel that presents with non-bloody diarrhoea, malabsorption (eg, steatorrhoea), abdominal pain (most commonly in the RLQ), oral ulcers, and perianal fistulas. Smoking increases the risk of CD. A few patients may also have constitutional symptoms (eg, low-grade fever, weight loss). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with CD are particularly at an increased risk of developing \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium oxalate stones\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because of fat malabsorption associated with CD. Normally, dietary calcium binds to the oxalate in the gut, thereby decreasing excess absorption of oxalate. In conditions that cause fat malabsorption (eg, CD), calcium binds to the fat, leaving oxalate unbound. Unbound oxalate is freely absorbed in the bloodstream. This leads to elevated oxalate levels in the blood which form calcium oxalate stones in the urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium phosphate stones\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with hyperparathyroidism and type 1 renal tubular acidosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystine stones\u003C/strong\u003E are usually seen in hereditary cystinuria. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium ammonium phosphate stones\u003C/strong\u003E are struvite stones usually seen in urinary tract infections with urease-producing bacteria (eg, Proteus). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUric acid stones\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in gout and conditions with high cell turnover (eg, leukaemia, polycythaemia, chemotherapy).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with Crohn\u0027s disease have an increased risk of developing calcium oxalate renal tract stones."],"references":["Gaspar SR, Mendon\u00e7a T, Oliveira P, Oliveira T, Dias J, Lopes T. Urolithiasis and crohn\u0027s disease. Urol Ann. 2016;8(3):297-304. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4944622/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28709"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2569"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28709"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-26T13:58:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-26T13:58:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2569"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43724"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi